Serratus anterior muscle

The serratus anterior muscle belongs to the chest muscles and originates on the front side of the first to eighth rib. It attaches from here to the edge of the shoulder blade. The serratus anterior muscle allows the outward movement (protraction) of the scapula and forward movement of the shoulder. It also causes rotation of the scapula and makes sure the scapula is kept against the chest.
